WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:07.280
You know, usually like when you look at a map of a city, you see the streets, you see the buildings, the parks, it all makes intuitive sense.

00:07.620 --> 00:10.320
Right. You can just trace a line from point A to point B.

00:10.320 --> 00:21.840
Exactly. You trace a line from your house to your office and the map provides this cohesive, unified picture of reality.

00:21.840 --> 00:32.900
But I want you to imagine for a second, if depending on what street you turn down, the actual foundational laws of the universe just, well, they just completely changed.

00:33.280 --> 00:34.100
That would be terrifying.

00:34.220 --> 00:38.480
It would be like you're walking down your own block and physics works normally, right?

00:38.880 --> 00:41.700
Gravity pulls you down. Momentum pushes you forward.

00:41.700 --> 00:50.100
But then you cross an intersection into a different neighborhood and suddenly the laws of thermodynamics are totally inverted.

00:50.100 --> 00:53.220
Heat flows from cold to hot.

00:53.940 --> 00:59.420
And then you turn a corner into the financial district and time itself is running backwards.

00:59.960 --> 01:03.140
Cause and effect have basically swapped places.

01:04.080 --> 01:08.080
I mean, navigating a space like that wouldn't just be confusing.

01:08.300 --> 01:12.640
It would be fundamentally impossible.

01:12.640 --> 01:22.740
If the underlying logic of reality shifts every single time you cross a boundary, there's no shared baseline to make a decision.

01:23.000 --> 01:27.940
You couldn't build a bridge, let alone, you know, a functioning society.

01:28.280 --> 01:38.620
And yet when you really step back and look at how we understand our world today, that is exactly the intellectual landscape we live in.

01:38.620 --> 01:42.540
We exist in this deeply, deeply fragmented reality.

01:42.720 --> 01:43.300
We really do.

01:43.400 --> 01:54.620
Because if you ask a physicist to explain the universe, they give you this system of, you know, cold, hard causality, deterministic equations, maybe some quantum probabilities.

01:55.500 --> 01:56.480
Yeah, it's all very mechanical.

01:56.820 --> 01:57.140
Right.

01:57.140 --> 02:06.280
But if you walk over to the economics department, they give you a world of rational actors, numerical value, transactional equilibrium.

02:07.140 --> 02:08.560
And then there's the philosophy department.

02:08.700 --> 02:09.160
Exactly.

02:09.520 --> 02:15.140
You sit alone in a quiet room and just examine your own subjective human experience.

02:15.140 --> 02:21.320
Like, the actual feeling of making a difficult choice or the sensation of time passing.

02:22.220 --> 02:27.380
And neither the physicist nor the economist can explain what is actually happening to you.

02:27.620 --> 02:28.140
Not at all.

02:28.200 --> 02:33.840
These frameworks all seem to operate by completely different, totally incompatible rules.

02:34.200 --> 02:36.920
It's a profound structural disconnect.

02:37.800 --> 02:41.860
Because physics has essentially, well, no room for human agency.

02:41.860 --> 02:50.920
Economics struggles to account for actual human meaning or qualitative well-being or, you know, ecological reality.

02:51.320 --> 02:51.380
Yeah.

02:51.900 --> 02:53.020
The stuff that actually matter.

02:53.140 --> 02:53.340
Right.

02:53.500 --> 03:05.380
And philosophy is just perpetually stuck in the middle, endlessly trying to figure out how your rich, internal, subjective experience of, like, listening to this conversation right now,

03:05.380 --> 03:13.040
how that could possibly arise from the blind mechanical interactions of atoms and molecules in your brain.

03:13.040 --> 03:16.320
Which brings us to our mission for this deep dive.

03:16.840 --> 03:23.880
Today, we are exploring this truly radical paper published in March, 2026 by an author named Fliction.

03:24.560 --> 03:32.060
It's titled Process, Projection, and Power Toward a Unified Ontology of Choice, Causality, and Value.

03:32.380 --> 03:33.200
Quite a mouthful.

03:33.200 --> 03:36.300
It is, and the ambition here is just staggering.

03:37.100 --> 03:41.600
Because this paper is attempting to build what it calls a unified ontology.

03:42.020 --> 03:47.740
A single, cohesive, mathematical, and philosophical framework that can explain all of it.

03:47.800 --> 03:50.120
All the different neighborhoods on that map you mentioned.

03:50.660 --> 03:51.260
Exactly.

03:51.640 --> 03:56.200
We're going to explore the deepest mysteries of the flow of time and human consciousness.

03:56.940 --> 03:59.960
Map that onto how you and I actually make choices.

03:59.960 --> 04:05.520
See how the invention of money fundamentally distorts the geometry of those choices.

04:06.320 --> 04:07.140
And finally...

04:07.140 --> 04:08.320
The really dense part.

04:08.380 --> 04:08.700
Oh yeah.

04:08.820 --> 04:17.000
Finally, look at a highly technical mathematical blueprint the author proposes for saving complex systems from total collapse.

04:17.240 --> 04:20.460
And I think it's crucial to lay out the core thesis right up front.

04:20.460 --> 04:35.480
The author argues that the reason we have all these disconnected, incompatible maps of reality is that for centuries, our traditional frameworks have been looking at the universe entirely backward.

04:36.060 --> 04:36.980
Backward how?

04:36.980 --> 04:43.740
Well, in classical science, we've treated reality as being made up of static objects or static states.

04:44.020 --> 04:46.740
We think the universe is fundamentally made of things.

04:46.860 --> 04:49.660
You know, particles, planets, people, dollars.

04:50.020 --> 04:52.760
And then just occasionally those things change.

04:52.820 --> 04:58.800
So like a universe made of billiard balls just sitting on a table waiting for the cue ball to strike them.

04:59.440 --> 05:02.160
The being is the default and the doing is secondary.

05:02.160 --> 05:02.640
Exactly.

05:04.080 --> 05:04.340
Yeah.

05:05.240 --> 05:08.400
But this paper completely inverts that paradigm.

05:08.800 --> 05:21.460
It argues that transitions, like processes, choices, the irreversible changes from one state to another, those are the actual fundamental building blocks of reality.

05:21.620 --> 05:22.160
Wow.

05:22.360 --> 05:22.580
Yeah.

05:22.780 --> 05:26.860
Everything we think of as a static thing is actually just a secondary projection.

05:26.860 --> 05:32.420
It's a temporary shadow cast by an underlying continuous process.

05:33.240 --> 05:37.640
It's an ontology of becoming rather than an ontology of being.

05:37.700 --> 05:37.920
Okay.

05:38.020 --> 05:38.940
Let's unpack this.

05:39.020 --> 05:41.900
We have a massive intellectual journey ahead of us.

05:42.000 --> 05:51.880
And before we really get into the mechanics, I just want to emphasize to you, the listener, that this paper touches on some incredibly heavy systemic topics.

05:51.960 --> 05:52.140
Yeah.

05:52.200 --> 05:53.080
It really goes there.

05:53.080 --> 05:59.760
It analyzes capitalism, the consolidation of corporate power, economic extraction, institutional decay.

06:00.180 --> 06:06.420
But our goal today is not to take any political sides or endorse any specific ideological viewpoint.

06:06.580 --> 06:07.380
Absolutely not.

06:07.380 --> 06:15.620
We are going to explore these concepts strictly as the formal, structural, and mathematical mechanics proposed by the author.

06:16.420 --> 06:21.740
We're treating this as an exploration of a deeply complex architectural model.

06:22.380 --> 06:31.440
Our job is simply to convey the fascinating structural arguments contained in the source material, regardless of where they point.

06:31.440 --> 06:34.460
Because the math doesn't care about politics.

06:34.900 --> 06:36.340
It cares about structure.

06:37.220 --> 06:51.160
And if we want to understand how a structure as complex as a global finance or systemic power operates within this new process ontology, we actually have to start at the very bottom.

06:51.380 --> 06:52.260
The very bottom.

06:52.420 --> 06:52.560
Yeah.

06:52.580 --> 06:57.120
We have to start with one of the most famous intractable problems in all of science.

06:57.320 --> 06:59.580
You're talking about the hard problem of consciousness.

06:59.780 --> 07:00.540
The very one.

07:00.540 --> 07:10.840
So for anyone listening who might not, you know, spend their weekends reading cognitive science journals, the standard hard problem was famously formulated by the philosopher David Chalmers.

07:10.840 --> 07:20.440
It basically asks, how does physical matter create the rich, subjective, qualitative experience of being alive?

07:20.960 --> 07:24.260
Like, we can map the neural correlates of the brain.

07:24.960 --> 07:29.760
We can see exactly how the visual cortex processes the wavelength of red light.

07:30.540 --> 07:36.500
But none of that mechanical data explains what it actually feels like to see the color red.

07:36.600 --> 07:38.060
The actual experience.

07:38.160 --> 07:38.540
Yeah.

07:39.180 --> 07:47.680
How do blind, unfeeling neurons firing in the dark of your skull turn into the taste of coffee or the feeling of grief?

07:47.680 --> 07:57.860
And for decades, scientists and philosophers have just banged their heads against the wall, trying to solve this by looking for some missing mechanism in the brain.

07:58.320 --> 08:04.720
But Fliction's paper argues that the hard problem isn't actually about how matter makes mind at all.

08:04.780 --> 08:05.200
No?

08:05.360 --> 08:05.480
No.

08:05.480 --> 08:12.340
The paper proposes that the hard problem is entirely a categorical mismatch about time.

08:12.840 --> 08:13.700
A mismatch about time.

08:13.780 --> 08:13.940
Okay.

08:14.260 --> 08:17.420
That is a massive pivot from standard neuroscience.

08:17.980 --> 08:22.600
Let's break down what the paper means by that, starting with how physics views time.

08:22.760 --> 08:23.000
Sure.

08:23.000 --> 08:30.500
If we look at fundamental physics, what the paper calls the third-person perspective, time is entirely symmetric.

08:31.000 --> 08:36.300
In the mathematical models of general relativity, for example, time is just another coordinate.

08:36.460 --> 08:39.540
It's literally no different than up, down, left, or right.

08:39.660 --> 08:40.220
So spatial.

08:40.740 --> 08:41.260
Exactly.

08:41.540 --> 08:47.120
All moments, past, present, and future, they're equally real and equally accessible in the math.

08:47.120 --> 08:53.600
There is basically no mathematical variable in fundamental physics for the concept of now.

08:54.120 --> 09:03.760
So, to a physicist looking purely at the equations, the universe is just this giant frozen block of four-dimensional space-time.

09:03.920 --> 09:12.800
The Big Bang, the Roman Empire, you listening to this deep dive right now, and the eventual heat death of the universe,

09:12.800 --> 09:17.500
they all just exist statically within the geometry of the math.

09:17.620 --> 09:17.800
Yeah.

09:17.900 --> 09:19.780
It's often called the block universe theory.

09:20.580 --> 09:24.680
From that third-person objective view, nothing is technically happening.

09:24.780 --> 09:25.860
Everything simply is.

09:26.080 --> 09:26.360
Okay.

09:27.000 --> 09:31.740
But your lived experience, the first-person perspective, is entirely different.

09:32.240 --> 09:35.440
The reality you and I inhabit is strictly asymmetric.

09:35.900 --> 09:38.700
The past is completely fixed and inaccessible.

09:38.700 --> 09:49.240
The future is completely open and unwritten, and you're trapped forever in this ever-moving, razor-thin sliver of experience called now.

09:49.860 --> 09:55.820
I was trying to visualize this profound disconnect when I was reading the paper, and here is how I think of it.

09:55.900 --> 09:58.980
Imagine you're watching a movie on a streaming service, right?

09:59.100 --> 09:59.680
Okay, yeah.

09:59.880 --> 10:07.100
The third-person perspective, the physics perspective, is the entire progress bar at the bottom of the screen.

10:07.100 --> 10:14.460
Every scene, from the opening credits to the finale, exists simultaneously on the server as data.

10:15.400 --> 10:20.480
To the server, there's no fundamental difference between minute 10 and minute 90.

10:20.660 --> 10:23.020
They're just spatial coordinates on a hard drive.

10:23.940 --> 10:28.060
That is a highly functional way to visualize the block universe.

10:28.260 --> 10:28.620
Thanks.

10:28.840 --> 10:30.100
And the first-person perspective.

10:30.100 --> 10:33.980
The first-person perspective is the actual playhead.

10:34.220 --> 10:39.340
It's the laser or the processing unit reading the data moment to moment.

10:39.860 --> 10:43.680
It only ever experiences one single frame at a time.

10:43.960 --> 10:46.960
It leaves a trail of watched frames behind it.

10:47.040 --> 10:48.200
That's the fixed past.

10:48.360 --> 10:51.780
And it looks toward an unplayed buffer, the open future.

10:52.200 --> 10:52.320
Right.

10:52.580 --> 10:57.540
The progress bar is symmetric, but the playhead's journey is aggressively asymmetric.

10:58.020 --> 10:59.540
It only moves in one direction.

10:59.540 --> 11:04.980
And this is exactly where the paper identifies the root of our fragmented reality.

11:06.340 --> 11:12.480
How has science historically dealt with this massive disconnect between the progress bar and the playhead?

11:12.560 --> 11:14.840
It usually sides with the progress bar, doesn't it?

11:15.160 --> 11:15.660
Exactly.

11:16.560 --> 11:26.440
Classical science usually treats the timeless symmetric progress, bar the objective math, as the ultimate fundamental truth of reality.

11:26.440 --> 11:30.120
And therefore, it treats your experience of the playhead.

11:30.120 --> 11:36.520
The feeling of time flowing, of making choices, of moving from the present into the future.

11:37.180 --> 11:42.660
It treats that as just a stubborn, persistent illusion created by human biology.

11:42.920 --> 11:46.280
It says that your feeling of now is just a trick of the brain.

11:46.280 --> 11:46.820
Right.

11:47.000 --> 11:50.200
But this paper flips that completely upside down.

11:50.340 --> 11:52.600
It is a total ontological inversion.

11:53.400 --> 11:57.180
The paper argues that the first person lived experience of time flowing.

11:57.700 --> 12:05.320
That irreversible transition from potentiality into actuality is the primary foundational feature of reality.

12:05.400 --> 12:05.700
Wow.

12:05.700 --> 12:09.920
The symmetric progress bar of physics is just an abstraction.

12:10.280 --> 12:15.780
It's a model we build from our position at the playhead to try and understand the patterns of what we've already watched.

12:16.420 --> 12:18.020
The transition is real.

12:18.600 --> 12:20.480
The static block is the illusion.

12:20.480 --> 12:31.260
Okay, if we accept this premise, that the transition, the flow of time itself, is the fundamental building block of the universe, what is it made of?

12:31.660 --> 12:34.980
How does the paper define a transition mathematically?

12:35.660 --> 12:41.480
Because it breaks this down into three irreducible elements, which it calls the triad of reality.

12:42.320 --> 12:44.840
Causality, choice, and change.

12:44.840 --> 12:51.900
In a traditional deterministic worldview, you only really have causality.

12:52.820 --> 12:56.360
State A inevitably and mechanically leads to state B.

12:56.880 --> 13:06.920
But Fliction argues that mathematically, you cannot derive the actual lived flow of reality without all three of these elements interacting.

13:07.320 --> 13:09.220
Let's walk through the mechanics of the triad.

13:09.320 --> 13:10.600
First, we have causality.

13:11.040 --> 13:14.060
But it's not the old billiard ball causality, is it?

13:14.060 --> 13:14.280
No.

13:14.400 --> 13:18.160
In this framework, causality represents the third-person structure.

13:18.600 --> 13:21.020
It is the set of allowed future possibilities.

13:21.860 --> 13:27.700
Given the current state of the universe, the underlying laws dictate a menu of possible next states.

13:28.240 --> 13:30.200
Causality doesn't pick what happens next.

13:30.340 --> 13:34.620
It strictly defines the boundaries of what is mathematically allowed to happen next.

13:34.720 --> 13:35.640
It writes the menu.

13:36.000 --> 13:37.500
Then comes the second element.

13:38.000 --> 13:38.440
Choice.

13:38.440 --> 13:44.760
And I want to be very careful here, because we aren't just talking about human beings pondering what to eat for lunch.

13:45.760 --> 13:51.380
Choice, in this generalized ontological sense, is the first-person agency.

13:51.940 --> 13:59.780
It is the specific selection operator that picks one single path from that menu of causal possibilities.

13:59.780 --> 14:06.040
It is the mechanism that collapses the multiple potentials into a singular direction.

14:06.640 --> 14:08.100
And finally, change.

14:08.460 --> 14:13.140
Change is the irreversible actualization of that choice into history.

14:13.920 --> 14:24.460
It is the permanent act of taking that select impossibility and appending it to the record of the past, rendering it completely fixed and unalterable.

14:24.460 --> 14:30.200
Now, I have to push back here, because if you have a background in physics, your alarm bells are probably ringing right now.

14:30.200 --> 14:30.880
Oh, absolutely.

14:31.220 --> 14:38.800
If physics says the universe is governed by fundamental forces and quantum mechanics, where does choice actually live in the math?

14:39.320 --> 14:48.620
Are we suggesting that human free will or some cosmic consciousness is magically altering the trajectory of atoms in defiance of physics?

14:48.840 --> 14:50.660
It's a vital skepticism.

14:50.660 --> 14:55.000
The paper is absolutely not arguing for magic.

14:55.860 --> 15:01.380
This is where it introduces one of its most elegant mathematical concepts to bridge the gap.

15:01.900 --> 15:07.100
The dual aspect of indeterminacy, or what it calls the hard randomness symmetry.

15:07.960 --> 15:09.440
Let's dig into the math of this.

15:09.700 --> 15:15.380
How does the paper reconcile indeterminate quantum events with the concept of choice?

15:15.700 --> 15:18.640
Think about a highly unpredictable event.

15:18.640 --> 15:27.420
This could be a quantum superposition collapsing, or a highly complex non-linear event in a human neural network.

15:27.940 --> 15:33.360
There's a transition that cannot be perfectly predicted simply by looking at the past states.

15:33.560 --> 15:38.240
An indeterminate transition, we don't know exactly what will happen until it happens.

15:38.420 --> 15:38.700
Right.

15:39.100 --> 15:40.980
Now, how do we describe that event?

15:40.980 --> 15:53.600
The paper proves mathematically that an external third-person observer, someone looking at this system from the outside, can only describe this unpredictable event using a probability distribution.

15:53.800 --> 15:55.400
Because they can't see the whole picture.

15:55.920 --> 15:56.360
Exactly.

15:56.760 --> 16:01.220
To the outside observer, it looks like randomness or stochastic noise.

16:01.220 --> 16:06.420
They lack the internal contextual information, so they just see a dice roll.

16:06.980 --> 16:12.720
They see a 70% chance of outcome A and a 30% chance of outcome B.

16:12.900 --> 16:14.720
Because they are looking at the menu.

16:14.880 --> 16:16.560
They are studying the causality.

16:16.560 --> 16:17.280
Yes.

16:17.920 --> 16:33.200
But, and this is the theoretical breakthrough, a first-person observer looking from the inside of that exact same system, experiencing that exact same indeterminate transition, experiences it as choice.

16:33.380 --> 16:33.940
Whoa.

16:34.480 --> 16:39.620
Randomness and choice are not two different phenomena fighting for control of the universe.

16:40.020 --> 16:44.260
They are two different informational descriptions of the exact same event.

16:44.260 --> 16:48.780
I want to make sure the listener really grasps this, because it's mind-bending.

16:49.280 --> 16:55.820
The paper uses category theory to formalize this, specifically pointing to adjoint functors.

16:56.380 --> 17:03.600
Now, in mathematics, a functor is basically a mapping that translates the structure of one mathematical category into another.

17:03.740 --> 17:04.220
Precisely.

17:04.340 --> 17:09.460
It preserves the relationships between objects when you move them to a new context.

17:09.460 --> 17:28.660
So, if I understand the paper's proof, it's saying that when you apply a forgetful functor, meaning you strip away the internal, subjective, first-person context of an event to look at it objectively, the math literally collapses into pure probability.

17:28.860 --> 17:29.460
It becomes randomness.

17:29.460 --> 17:30.280
randomness.

17:30.420 --> 17:30.700
Yes.

17:30.700 --> 17:44.000
But when you apply the free functor, adding the internal lived context back into the equation, that exact same mathematical event resolves into the geometry of choice.

17:44.180 --> 17:46.300
It's the exact mechanism.

17:46.520 --> 17:47.720
They're dual aspects.

17:47.720 --> 17:56.060
Like, if I'm watching you deliberate over a difficult career decision, I cannot possibly compute the entirety of your internal state.

17:56.520 --> 18:01.260
To me, from the outside, you have a probabilistic chance of quitting your job or staying.

18:01.460 --> 18:03.300
It looks like a stochastic equation.

18:03.400 --> 18:03.760
Sure.

18:03.940 --> 18:06.580
But inside your mind, you aren't rolling a die.

18:06.840 --> 18:11.960
You are weighing the options, feeling the friction of the decision, and actively selecting a path.

18:11.960 --> 18:19.860
So, the randomness I see is just the shadow cast by your internal choice, simply because I don't have access to your first-person perspective.

18:20.400 --> 18:20.760
Yes.

18:21.620 --> 18:27.420
And this brings us to the paper's ultimate, staggering conclusion about the hard problem.

18:28.200 --> 18:34.780
Consciousness is not some magical substance or emergent smoke generated by complex brain matter.

18:35.760 --> 18:39.940
Consciousness is the internal experience of temporal asymmetry.

18:39.940 --> 18:48.500
It is simply what it feels like from the inside to resolve multiple possibilities into a single irreversible history.

18:49.140 --> 18:54.620
If you are the playhead moving across the data, consciousness is the friction of that movement.

18:54.820 --> 18:55.160
Exactly.

18:55.440 --> 19:01.420
It's the sensation of the transition itself that completely reshapes how we view our place in the universe.

19:01.820 --> 19:03.880
We aren't objects that have consciousness.

19:04.360 --> 19:07.360
We are the active process of time flowing.

19:07.360 --> 19:09.580
It shifts the foundation entirely.

19:10.480 --> 19:13.180
Reality isn't a static collection of objects.

19:13.600 --> 19:18.200
It is an endless sequence of choices resolving into irreversible history.

19:18.500 --> 19:20.760
But that creates a massive new problem.

19:21.180 --> 19:26.200
If reality is just this endless sequence of choices, who or what is actually making them?

19:26.800 --> 19:34.500
In a framework where objects don't fundamentally exist, we have to completely throw out our traditional definition of what a person is.

19:34.500 --> 19:35.060
We do.

19:35.060 --> 19:41.520
Which brings us to the paper's second major phase, redefining the self and the geometry of possibility.

19:42.100 --> 19:48.540
If we accept the premise that processes are fundamental, you cannot define yourself by your physical body.

19:48.860 --> 19:51.000
I mean, your cells replace themselves constantly.

19:51.440 --> 19:53.580
Your physical state is always in flux.

19:53.880 --> 19:53.960
Right.

19:54.280 --> 20:00.680
You also cannot define yourself as a static, unchanging soul floating somewhere outside of time.

20:00.680 --> 20:03.840
So how does flexion define the human identity?

20:04.240 --> 20:10.720
Because the paper introduces this formal mathematical definition of the self, represented as an ordered pair.

20:11.740 --> 20:17.280
The equation is S sub T equals H sub T omega sub T.

20:18.060 --> 20:20.540
Let's translate this into English for the listener.

20:20.740 --> 20:24.100
The first variable, H sub T, is your history.

20:24.700 --> 20:28.360
And the second variable, omega sub T, is your horizon.

20:28.360 --> 20:29.860
History and horizon.

20:30.120 --> 20:31.100
Let's start with history.

20:31.420 --> 20:32.240
H sub T.

20:32.240 --> 20:38.580
Your history is the irreversible, append-only record of every event, every choice, and every

20:38.580 --> 20:41.740
transition that has ever happened to you or been made by you.

20:42.080 --> 20:47.020
It is the absolute sum of your past, recorded in strict chronological order.

20:47.840 --> 20:53.580
Crucially, in this math, history can never be erased, altered, or uncollapsed.

20:54.020 --> 20:55.400
It is permanently fixed.

20:55.400 --> 21:00.920
Okay, and based on that fixed history, we get the second variable, omega sub T, the horizon.

21:01.560 --> 21:06.740
The horizon is your constrained space of possible futures.

21:07.380 --> 21:13.500
It is the specific, mathematically defined set of possibilities that are open to you right

21:13.500 --> 21:18.880
now in this exact moment, based entirely on what has happened in your history.

21:18.880 --> 21:26.000
To help visualize this, let's think about how an RPG video game works, with those complex

21:26.000 --> 21:29.400
skill trees, or like a massive branching narrative.

21:29.840 --> 21:34.580
Let's use the concept of a high-dimensional manifold, or a phase space.

21:35.120 --> 21:41.140
Imagine your life is a point moving through this massive, multidimensional web of paths.

21:41.140 --> 21:49.280
Your history, your H sub T, is the exact unchangeable red line you've drawn through that web from the

